Democracy without Civic Connection
Something has befallen democracy in the sense that the government is elected by the people, all over the world.
Somehow, people have lost faith in elections.
Voter turnout is declining in many countries; in the case of European Parliament elections, voter turnout was so ridiculously low that the legitimacy of the election results is questionable.
Aside from voter turnout, we have become accustomed to considering parties or candidates who receive 25% of the cast votes as "winners".
From Holland to Finland to Argentina and Japan, majority governments are formed on the basis of minorities.
Even the apparent exceptions do not prove the opposite.
Only a few American presidents were elected by more than 10% of eligible voters. In fact, half of eligible voters in the USA have not even registered to participate in the election; of those who have registered, half do not vote; of those who do vote, less than half vote for the winner.
Even Tony Blair's "earth-shattering" majority in the British House of Commons is on shaky ground: The Labour Party received only about 40% of the votes in the last election in 2002 and that with a voter turnout of 60%.
Thus, only 24% of the total electorate supported Blair's party.
In most countries, the elections look very different now compared to twenty or even fifty years ago.
What has happened?
One possible answer could be that voters distrust political parties.
The voting democracy works in most countries due to the mediation of organizations that put forward candidates who enter for specific packages of political possibilities, for a "manifesto" or a "party program."
For a number of reasons, this well-established practice that has worked over a long period of time no longer functions.
Ideological party programs have lost their strength; voters no longer accept the packages tied up by the parties, they want to take something for themselves and choose.
Furthermore, the political parties have become machines that consist of tightly organized cores of insiders.
The paradox here is that the parties have become even more clique-like with the loss of their specific ideological orientation.
It is more important for them to belong than to share specific convictions.
Such developments have alienated the parties from the voter.
Since most people do not want to belong to a special party, only a minority plays the party game.
This is why public suspicion of political parties has increased, last but not least, because it is - like in professional sports - expensive to participate.
If the costs are borne by the taxpayer, it is disliked.
However, without state financial support, parties would have to obtain money through channels that are often dubious, if not even unlawful.
Many of the major political scandals of the past decades began with the financing of parties and their candidates.
Other indicators - such as the clear decline in membership - confirm that the parties have become unpopular.
Nevertheless, parties are indispensable for a direct democracy.
The result is a clear separation between the visible political actors and the electorate.
Since the parties are active in parliament, the effects of this separation concern one of the crucial institutions of democracy.
People no longer believe that the parliaments represent them and thus equipped with the necessary legitimacy to make decisions on their behalf.
At this point, a second, rather independent development comes into play.
The people are more impatient today than ever before.
As consumers, they are accustomed to immediate satisfaction.
However, as voters, they have to wait until they feel the results of the election, which they made at the ballot box.
They sometimes never see the desired results.
Democracy doesn't need time only for the elections, but also for discussions and well-considered weighing.
The consumer as a voter won't accept this, however, and turns away as a result.
There are alternatives. However, each has its own problems as a democratic solution.
The "Direct Action" through demonstrations became a regular and often effective event.
For less mobile people, it could be replaced by the possibility of being able to express their opinion electronically; this ranges from internet chat rooms to electronic messages to political leaders.
Then there are the non-governmental organizations. They often have undemocratic internal structures, but seem to be still closer connected to the citizens.
Furthermore, there is, of course, the possibility of completely disengaging and leaving politics to the experts, in order to focus on other priorities in life.
That latter actually harbors the greatest risks, because it promotes the creeping authoritarianism, which is a sign of our times.
But also the other signs of the separation between politics and citizens create a rather insecure state, because no one can say anymore how representative the prevailing opinions are.
Some want to get to the bottom of the knot by means of more direct democracy.
However, an enduring connection between leaders and followers cannot be established by reducing public discussion to simple voting alternatives.
There are even more arguments to be made for holding on to the classical institutions of parliamentary democracy and trying to reconnect them more closely with the citizenry.
After all, unpopular parties and declining voter turnout could prove to be a mere temporary phenomenon.
New parties could emerge and inject more life into elections and representative governments.
However, it is likely that this would not be enough to restore the general legitimacy that elected governments have lost.
Therefore, the first concern of all those who have the constitution of freedom at heart must be to rethink democracy and its institutions.
